text: This movie is probably going racist towards Africans. Brimming with sterotypes that probably aren't even apart of any African nation's culture. As ppl have mentioned before they r treating the entire continent as it is one great giant "black safari" country. This idiotic idea has perpetuated in American culture enough. Yes, ppl can simply say that are going on a trip to Europe or Asia; however, that is usually followed up with what region or countries they plan to visit. "I am going to Spain, France, Belgium, Italy, the UK, a European tour etc." I'm going to Dubai" or "I'm going to Singapore" WHERE THE HELL IN AFRICA R U VISITING? West Africa: Nigeria?(my blood) Ghana? Ivory Coast, Senegal or Mauritania? East Africa: Kenya? Rwanda? Ethiopia? South Africa: Zimbabwe, Botswana, the country of South Africa? Central: Congo? Chad? Camaroon?North Africa: Egypt, Morocco, Lybia? Tunsia? There are 54 damn nations in Africa. It's really quite simple. As a young second generation African I find this highly irritating, so do others. Americans tend to be utterly ignorant of the cultures, histories and especially geography of this world. I cannot fathom why this is still going on in 2014 and it's getting quite old.
author: Jade Baratheon

text: I went to see this last week after watching 50 First Dates and the Wedding Singer several days prior. It’s certainly not as bad as people are making it out to be, sure there’s the odd non-funny stupid joke but with emotionally touching scenes and the on-screen chemistry between Sandler and Barrymore the movie is definitely a worthwhile watch. I enjoyed Adam & Drew's previous film collaborations in the Wedding Singer and 50 First Dates. In my opinion, despite what the box office figures and critics say, Blended is another great film with these two great actors, go and see it, you will enjoy yourself!

text: So much for looking through comments to see if the movie itself is good, instead a shit ton of hate comments about an actor they hate and yet clicked on a video knowing he was in it. Seriously, YouTube has become a dumpster full of crybabies, and roid raged internet tough guys. I understand maturity is in short supply nowadays, but does anyone have any input on the actual video itself, instead of getting your shit pushed in over what country it was filmed about, or the fact they weren't specific as to WHERE in Africa. Was it funny, cute, sad, serious, or slapstick? Humor wise, what other Sandler movie can it be compared to? Is it worth a theater ticket, or a rental? If you hate Adam Sandler that's fine, however, wouldn't it be more prudent to go to an anti Adam Sandler video to post why you agree instead of going to a video of someone you hate to troll? There's a difference between playing devil's advocate, and being an asshole. There are people in different countries worrying every day about their next meal, or surviving each day through sickness, and thirst, and YouTube is where the better off go to worry about not being specific on the location of said countries. Thumbs down this comment if you're part of the problem.

text: The movie, altogether, was a happy and good one. It has a good ending! However, it was not as good as "50 First Dates" or "The Wedding Singer," i.e. 2 other movies Drew Barrymore and Adam Sandler co-starred in. I like those movies way more because he is actually sweet her in those movies. In this movie, NOT so much :(  From this movie, I really liked that Lauren is a good, caring mom who is sweet to her two boys, She tries to be there for them in every way possible and make them happy with all she can. I liked that Lauren had such a great coworker, who was also a best friend. That friend was really nice and always there for Lauren to defend and support her. I liked the romance between Lauren's best friend and Jim's boss. I really liked that Jim tried his best to be a good father to his three daughters, although he messed up so many times. He loved his wife so much!!! The movie showed those beautifully. I liked that Jim's best friend at work tried to stand up for Jim's daughter Hillary when someone upset her by thinking she was a guy. I loved how patient and nice Jim was to Lauren's sons. He was a true father figure. I loved how sweet Lauren was to Jim's daughters. She gave proper attention to each of them. She understood all their personal feelings, accepted them, and helped them out with small yet sweet gestures. I loved that Lauren's older son did his best to defend his mom against Jim and Jim's kids' behavior. I liked that Jake liked Hillary and accepted her for who she was: an athlete with special dietary needs.  I like how crazy Jake's dad and his stepmom were for each other because it looked like no matter how long they stayed together, they would NEVER become tired of one other. I loved when Jim and his daughters showed up for Tyler's game to cheer for him and support him. I loved how Jim helped Tyler with that baseball game.    There were soo many things I HATED in the movie.   -One of Lauren's kid sprayed Fire Extinguisher at their hired babysitter. I suppose it was done to show the naughtiness of boys, but really, showing something like this might give children or anyone else ideas to do similar things.  -Jim was a jerk to Lauren most of the movie. Here are some times: 1) He was looking at the TV while addressing her instead of at her at the Hooters' date. I found that very disrespectful. I know he did not find her interesting at that time, but despite that, he should have showed her some courtesy. 2) he embarrassed her in front of the cashier at the store,   3) he said crude things to her outside of the store,  4) he was mean to her in front of her coworker and friend 5) he was mean to her just because she helped his daughter Hillary (Bella Thorne) get a makeover, 6) he scared Lauren to death when he took her son out to ride the weird ostrich but did not apologize until way later, 7) he flicked his nails on Lauren's neck after they kissed at the end of the movie even though he knew it hurt her [I know she giggled while saying it hurts, but since it actually hurt, he should not have done that]   -They overdid it in portraying Lauren's difficulty to carry Tyler, her younger son, to bed. He is a little boy. Although he is growing up, he is not so heavy that she would have to carry him in that manner and repeatedly bang his head on every corner and doorway. THEY OVERDID THE BANGING THE HEAD part!! Seriously, a real mom would not have allowed their child's head to bang on the door frame soo many time. She would have shifted the child's head to try to prevent it, or maybe try to go through the door differently so that the child's head would not bang. I sincerely hope that it was a plastic figure in her hand Drew Barrymore was carrying during all the banging-head scenes.   -I hated how they showed Lauren's older son having a crush on his nanny. It was creepy.   -Lauren was portrayed as a sweet person who has no spunk throughout much of the movie. 1) She let Jim (Adam Sandler) talk to her and treat in that insulting manner without really defending herself.  Seriously, towards the end of the movie, her husband tried to get back with her and she stood firm and strong against it. I was like, WHERE THE HELL WAS YOUR STRONG ATTITUDE DURING THE REST OF THE MOVIE, LADY? Couldn't you have been like this  when Jim was a jerk to you? You let Jim walk all over you without saying much of anything to discourage such behavior! 2) She took too long to agree in putting Jim's youngest daughter to bed.  -I hated the husband of that Indian(or was Pakistani?) couple.  1) His wife looked at this group of male singers performing and smiled in a lecherous way. He tapped her rather sharply on the shoulder and gave her a dirty look to make her stop looking 2) His wife was looking at Lauren and smiling when Lauren came down the stairs specially dressed for the last day of the Africa visit. He also tapped her rather sharply then.   - Jake, Hillary's boyfriend, asked her out AFTER Hillary had the makeover. Although he showed interest in her before the makeover, he did not so much as talk to her. Is the movie showing that athletic tomboyish dressed girl do not get asked out? Even if that is true, movies can go any way a director wants it to be. They could have shown that even if no one noticed her as a girl in her athletic garb, he did They did show that. However, he did not ask her out BEFORE she had a girly makeover. Does a girl have to look pretty and gorgeous with her makeup and outfits before a guy publicly pays attention to her? That thought upset me.   -Jake looked at his stepmom's cleavage towards the end of the video chat. How gross!
